04767nam a22006495i 9780231548489DE-B159720220426115627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220426t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021038277  a97802315484897 a10.7312/tarb189722doi  a(DE-B1597)624601  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJK325 4aJK325b.T37 2022 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a321.02/09732231 aTarbert, Jesse, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhen Good Government Meant Big Government :bThe Quest to Expand Federal Power, 1913–1933 /cJesse Tarbert. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tChapter One. ADMINISTRATION AND ACCOMMODATION -- tChapter Two. THE ELITE REFORMERS IN EXILE -- tChapter Three. AFTER THE ARMISTICE -- tChapter Four. THE BUDGET DEBATE -- tChapter Five. THE DARK HORSE -- tChapter Six. EARLY SUCCESS -- tChapter Seven. EQUAL PROTECTION UNDER LAW -- tChapter Eight. BACKLASH -- tChapter Nine. SOUTHERN STRENGTH -- tChapter Ten. CONGRESSIONAL COUNTEROFFENSIVE -- tChapter Eleven. LOW EXPECTATIONS -- tChapter Twelve. THE GREAT ENGINEER -- tChapter Thirteen. DASHED HOPES -- tCONCLUSION -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe years after World War I have often been seen as an era when Republican presidents and business leaders brought the growth of government in the United States to a sudden and emphatic halt. In When Good Government Meant Big Government, the historian Jesse Tarbert inverts the traditional story by revealing a forgotten effort by business-allied reformers to expand federal power—and how that effort was foiled by Southern Democrats and their political allies.Tarbert traces how a loose-knit coalition of corporate lawyers, bankers, executives, genteel reformers, and philanthropists emerged as the leading proponents of central control and national authority in government during the 1910s and 1920s. Motivated by principles of “good government” and using large national corporations as a model, these elite reformers sought to transform the federal government’s ineffectual executive branch into a modern organization with the capacity to solve national problems. They achieved some success during the presidency of Warren G. Harding, but the elite reformers’ support for federal antilynching legislation confirmed the worries of white Southerners who feared that federal power would pose a threat to white supremacy. Working with others who shared their preference for local control of public administration, Southern Democrats led a backlash that blocked enactment of the elite reformers’ broader vision for a responsive and responsible national government.Offering a novel perspective on politics and policy in the years before the New Deal, this book sheds new light on the roots of the modern American state and uncovers a crucial episode in the long history of racist and antigovernment forces in American life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aFederal governmentzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic administrationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/tarb1897240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231548489423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231548489/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL 